         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">Christmasday, ¶ 1866 ¶  ¶ I am sorry, dear Dr Hooker, that you taxed your department so heavily in freight for the Willows &amp; Succulents you so kindly sent by mail steamer I must not induce you to make...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">66.12.25d</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">To Joseph Hooker</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RBG Kew, Kew correspondence, Australia, Mueller, 1858-70, ff. 247-8.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">Christmasday,</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">1866<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">MS annotations: by D. Oliver? </seg>Alsomitra <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">and</seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">J. Hooker</seg> Ansd [Feby] 22/67. [Letter not found.]</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am sorry, dear Dr Hooker, that you taxed your department so heavily in freight for the Willows &amp; Succulents you so kindly sent by mail steamer I must not induce you to make again such sacrifices, but rather risk the sendings by the clippers, which arrive usually in about 80 days.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See J. Hooker to M, 19 October 1866. The Mail Steamer route involved mail crossing the desert by rail between the Mediterranean and Red Sea, with some being sent by rail to either Trieste or Marseilles, and the remainder taking slightly longer by sea from Southampton; the clippers sailed the much longer route via Cape of Good Hope.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>My Garden assistant unpacked the consignment and reports thereon<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Report not found.</p>
               </note> - <name key="Dracaena%20Draco">Dracaena Draco</name> is growing famously.<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See J. Hooker to M, 1 March 1866.</p>
               </note> Will we have here an [Orotama] tree<note xml:id="ftn5" type="footnote" n="5">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Orotava? Large specimens of the Dragon tree grow at La Oratava, Teneriffe. A reputed ancient specimen was destroyed in a storm in March 1867; see A. Gray (1868), who commented 'the age of 6000 years which has been assigned to it by some of the "most sober naturalists" may not be very greaty exaggerated'. </p>
               </note> after thousand years? or less. I find the Dracaenaceous plant of rapid growth &amp; the magnificent palmlike NZ species I use in masses to decorate my pine forest, as it were with tropical features. I have abolished <name key="Dracaenopis">Dracaenopis</name>
               <note xml:id="ftn6" type="footnote" n="6">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Dracaenopsis?</p>
               </note> &amp; <name key="Charlwoodia">Charlwoodia</name> &amp; <name key="Calodracon">Calodracon</name> as genera, and distinguish Dracaena &amp; <name key="Cordyline">Cordyline</name> by the structure of albumen &amp; size of Embryo. Thus <name key="Cordyline">Cordyline</name> has two <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">sections</hi>
               </seg>, the species with uniovulate fruit-cells = <name key="Eucordyline">Eucordyline</name> &amp; those with many ovules = <name key="Charlwoodia">Charlwoodia</name>.<note xml:id="ftn7" type="footnote" n="7">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 9pt; margin-left: 0in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>See B66.12.04, pp. 194-7. </p>
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>There is a blank page on the left of f. 247 front, where continuation text would normally be expected; the following text, f. 248, may be part of a different letter.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The enclosed is a list of Orchids sent to you by <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">this</hi>
               </seg>
               <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">mail</hi>
               </seg> through the agency of Mess. Rob Gower &amp; Coy of Marseilles. <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>I took great pains to procure so extensive a collection of these pretty little things &amp; I shall about as many more kinds to send when the stem[s] of the later flowering species have fully died down in the pots<note xml:id="ftn8" type="footnote" n="8">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva; margin-left: 0.3346in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3346in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>The text ends without valediction at the foot of the front of f. 248. List not found; no entry for receipt of such a consignment has been found in the Kew Inwards Books.</p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
